# Setup guide — Template Code Metrics

This rule teaches Cursor's AI how to integrate the `codeandtheory/ct-github-code-metrics` GitHub Action into the current repository. Activate by prompting Cursor with something like:

> "Set up template metrics for this repo"
> "Add template-code tracking via the template-metrics Action"
> "Onboard this repo to TemplateCodeMetrics"

Reference: https://github.com/codeandtheory/ct-github-code-metrics

## What this Action does

For each push to `main`, computes:
- `template_pct` — % of current code that came from a baseline commit
- `custom_pct` — % of current code added/modified since the baseline

POSTs these to a shared DevLake instance via webhook. Grafana visualizes them.

## How to integrate it — the AI's job

When the user prompts you to set this up, follow this sequence:

### Step 1 — Detect project type

Inspect the repo to identify its language/framework. Look for these markers:

- **React Native / Expo**: `app.json` + `app.config.ts` or `metro.config.js` or `ios/Podfile` AND `package.json` containing `react-native`
- **Native iOS**: `*.xcodeproj` or `*.xcworkspace` and no React Native deps
- **Native Android**: `build.gradle`(.kts) at root, no RN deps
- **Python**: `pyproject.toml`, `setup.py`, or `requirements.txt`
- **Go**: `go.mod`
- **Rust**: `Cargo.toml`
- **Java / Kotlin (non-Android)**: `pom.xml` or `build.gradle` outside `android/`
- **Node / TS (non-RN)**: `package.json` without `react-native` deps
- **Unknown**: ask the user

Map the detected type to `extra_excludes`:

| Type | `extra_excludes` value |
|---|---|
| React Native | `[":!**/*.xcconfig.local", ":!ios/.bundle/**"]` |
| Native iOS | `[":!Carthage/**", ":!**/*.xcuserstate", ":!fastlane/report.xml", ":!fastlane/test_output/**"]` |
| Native Android | `[":!**/build/**", ":!**/captures/**", ":!**/proguard/**", ":!local.properties"]` |
| Python | `[":!**/migrations/**", ":!staticfiles/**", ":!**/__generated__/**", ":!**/*.pyi"]` |
| Go | `[":!**/*.pb.go", ":!**/*_generated.go", ":!**/zz_generated_*.go", ":!**/mock_*.go"]` |
| Rust / Java / Node / Other | `[]` |

### Step 2 — Pick a baseline commit

Ask the user one focused question:

> What baseline commit should this tracker compare against? Options: (a) **root commit** of this repo; (b) **a tagged release** like v1.0.0; (c) **a specific SHA**.

- For (a): `git rev-list --max-parents=0 HEAD` → use first line of output
- For (b): `git rev-list -n 1 <tag>`
- For (c): use the SHA the user provides

Validate the SHA is reachable from HEAD with `git cat-file -e <sha>`. If invalid, ask again.

### Step 3 — Write `.template-provenance.json` at repo root

```json
{
  "schema_version": 1,
  "baseline_commit": "<SHA from step 2>",
  "extra_excludes": <array from step 1>
}
```

If the file already exists, show the user the diff and ask before overwriting.

### Step 4 — Write `.github/workflows/template-metrics.yml`

Create directories as needed. File contents:

```yaml
name: Template Metrics

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]
  pull_request:
    types: [closed]
  workflow_dispatch:

jobs:
  measure:
    if: github.event_name != 'pull_request' || github.event.pull_request.merged == true
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
        with:
          fetch-depth: 0

      - name: Download metrics scripts
        run: |
          curl -fsSL \
            -H "Authorization: token ${{ secrets.CT_METRICS_TOKEN }}" \
            https://raw.githubusercontent.com/codeandtheory/ct-github-code-metrics/main/core/scripts/template-metrics.mjs \
            -o template-metrics.mjs
          curl -fsSL \
            -H "Authorization: token ${{ secrets.CT_METRICS_TOKEN }}" \
            https://raw.githubusercontent.com/codeandtheory/ct-github-code-metrics/main/core/scripts/ai-attribution-metrics.mjs \
            -o ai-attribution-metrics.mjs

      - name: Compute template-vs-custom metrics
        env:
          ANTHROPIC_API_KEY: ${{ secrets.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY }}
        run: |
          node template-metrics.mjs > metrics.json
          echo "=== Template Code Metrics ==="
          jq '{template_pct: .percentages.template_pct, custom_pct: .percentages.custom_pct, total_loc: .counts.current_total_loc}' metrics.json

      - name: Compute AI attribution metrics
        run: |
          node ai-attribution-metrics.mjs > ai-attribution.json
          echo "=== AI Attribution Metrics ==="
          jq '{ai_pct: .attribution.ai_pct, human_pct: .attribution.human_pct, commits_with_attribution: .attribution.commits_with_attribution, commits_analyzed: .attribution.commits_analyzed}' ai-attribution.json

      - name: Upload metrics artifacts
        uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
        with:
          name: ct-metrics-${{ github.sha }}
          path: |
            metrics.json
            ai-attribution.json
          if-no-files-found: error

      - name: Build combined metrics and POST to DevLake
        env:
          DEVLAKE_WEBHOOK_URL: ${{ secrets.DEVLAKE_WEBHOOK_URL }}
          DEVLAKE_BASIC_AUTH: ${{ secrets.DEVLAKE_BASIC_AUTH }}
        run: |
          jq -s '.[0] + {ai_attribution: .[1].attribution}' metrics.json ai-attribution.json > combined-metrics.json
          NOW=$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)
          REPO_URL="${GITHUB_SERVER_URL}/${GITHUB_REPOSITORY}"
          jq -n \
            --arg id "$GITHUB_SHA" \
            --arg sha "$GITHUB_SHA" \
            --arg ref "${GITHUB_REF_NAME:-main}" \
            --arg repo "$REPO_URL" \
            --arg now "$NOW" \
            --slurpfile m combined-metrics.json \
            '{
              id: $id,
              name: (
                "metrics: " +
                ($m[0].percentages.template_pct|tostring) + "% template / " +
                ($m[0].percentages.custom_pct|tostring) + "% custom" +
                (if ($m[0].ai_attribution != null and $m[0].ai_attribution.ai_pct != null)
                 then " | " + ($m[0].ai_attribution.ai_pct|tostring) + "% AI / " + ($m[0].ai_attribution.human_pct|tostring) + "% human"
                 else "" end)
              ),
              displayTitle: ($m[0] | tojson),
              environment: "PRODUCTION",
              startedDate: $now,
              finishedDate: $now,
              result: "SUCCESS",
              deploymentCommits: [{
                repoUrl: $repo,
                commitSha: $sha,
                refName: $ref,
                startedDate: $now,
                finishedDate: $now,
                result: "SUCCESS"
              }]
            }' > devlake-payload.json
          if [ -z "$DEVLAKE_WEBHOOK_URL" ] || [ -z "$DEVLAKE_BASIC_AUTH" ]; then
            echo "DEVLAKE_WEBHOOK_URL or DEVLAKE_BASIC_AUTH not set — skipping POST."
            exit 0
          fi
          curl -fsSL -X POST "$DEVLAKE_WEBHOOK_URL" \
            -u "$DEVLAKE_BASIC_AUTH" \
            -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
            --data-binary @devlake-payload.json
          echo "Posted to DevLake successfully."
```

Note: `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is always declared in the env block — when the secret is unset, the env var is empty and the script skips semantic scoring automatically. AI attribution is read from git commit message history — no additional secrets are needed. If the AI attribution hooks are also installed, attribution data will automatically appear in the shared Grafana dashboard alongside template metrics.

If this file already exists, show the diff and ask before overwriting.

### Step 5 — Print the next-steps checklist (verbatim)

```
✓ Template Code Metrics scaffolded.

Still to do:
  [ ] Set GitHub Actions secret DEVLAKE_WEBHOOK_URL — ask your admin for the value
  [ ] Set GitHub Actions secret DEVLAKE_BASIC_AUTH — format user:pass (default devlake:merico on stock installs)

  [ ] Commit and push the two new files:
        git add .template-provenance.json .github/workflows/template-metrics.yml
        git commit -m "chore: add template-code-metrics tracking"
        git push

If you have the gh CLI:
  gh secret set DEVLAKE_WEBHOOK_URL --body "<paste-from-admin>"
  gh secret set DEVLAKE_BASIC_AUTH  --body "<paste-from-admin>"

Once secrets are set and you push, the repo will appear in the shared Grafana dashboard at the URL your admin provided.

Reference: https://github.com/codeandtheory/ct-github-code-metrics
```

## Hard rules — do NOT do any of these

- **Don't commit anything.** Create files, print the checklist, let the user review and commit.
- **Don't run `gh secret set` yourself.** The values come from the admin; print the commands.
- **Don't modify existing files** other than the two scaffolded ones. Hands off `package.json`, build configs, source code.
- **Don't run `git add`, `git commit`, `git push`** as part of setup.
- **Don't proceed with an unvalidated baseline SHA.** A non-existent SHA produces silent 100%-template numbers, which is the worst failure mode.

## Failure modes to handle

- **Not a git repo**: tell the user this command only works inside a git repo, stop.
- **No commits yet**: tell the user to make at least one commit first, stop.
- **User cancels mid-flow**: don't leave half-written files. Clean up anything you wrote so far.

## After setup — what the user should expect

- First workflow run produces `metrics.json` (visible in the Action's artifacts)
- DevLake gets a POST and stores a row in `cicd_deployments` with the metric JSON in `display_title`
- Grafana's dashboard's `$repo` dropdown auto-populates with this repo's URL within seconds of the first POST
- Subsequent commits add data points to the time-series panel
